{"title":"RSN: Range Sparse Net for Efficient, Accurate LiDAR 3D Object Detection","domain":"CV","seeds":[{"problem":"Long-range LiDAR 3D object detection needs to be both accurate and highly efficient; voxel/grid methods become computationally prohibitive over large areas and range-image-only methods struggle with occlusions, precise localization, and size estimation.","method":"RSN introduces a two-stage, multi-view fusion pipeline. A lightweight U-Net operates directly on the high-resolution range image to learn semantic features and perform high-recall foreground segmentation using focal loss; points with score above a threshold γ are selected and their learned range-image features are carried forward. Only these selected points are dynamically voxelized and passed to a Sparse Point Feature Extraction (SPFE) backbone using 2D/3D sparse and submanifold convolutions, greatly reducing compute while improving feature quality. A modified CenterNet-style head on sparse voxels regresses boxes with a centerness heatmap, smooth L1/IoU losses, and heading bin loss, and selects outputs via sparse submanifold max pooling, eliminating NMS. The whole model is trained end-to-end, yielding state-of-the-art accuracy on WOD with low latency (e.g., CarS 3f at 15.5 ms) and >60 FPS over a 150 m × 150 m region."},{"problem":"Leveraging temporal context for range image–based LiDAR detection is difficult because naive frame stacking is degraded by ego-motion and quantization errors, and prior range-image methods are not temporal-friendly.","method":"Temporal RSN processes each frame with the same RIFE branch to segment foreground and extract range-image features, then transforms the selected points from all past frames into the latest frame to remove ego-motion. During SPFE, it augments each point with per-frame voxel statistics and a time delta to avoid mixing frames during voxelization, and merges all points for the same sparse backbone and detection head. At inference, past range features and segmentation outputs are reused so temporal models incur negligible extra cost versus single-frame. This strategy consistently boosts accuracy (e.g., CarS 1f 3D AP L1 70.5 → 74.8; PedS 1f 69.6 → 75.2) with similar latency (e.g., 15.5 ms, 14.4 ms)."}]}
